After upgrading to `Version 0.169.0 (0.169.0)`, in my user stylesheet, this used to work:

``` css
.editor-colors, :host {
    background-color: #222222;
}
```

Do I now have to do this?

``` css
.editor{
    background:#222;
}
```

I get a weird problem when applying auto-indentation to following code. When calling a function with a callback and finally the closing bracket in a new line everything from the closing bracket on get indented incorrectly.

I think Atom reduces the indentation when the callback's closing curly bracket closes. 
JSBeautify indents the callback by one to make it clearer.

I've come across this problem looking into [atom-jshint](https://github.com/Joezo/atom-jshint/blob/master/lib/atom-jshint.js#L16-L33) where it is indented correctly.

Atom version:0.169.0
OS: Win7

The behaviour I would expect based on JSBeautify:

``` js
function outer(){

    fnWithCallback('someLongAttributeikeAnEventString', 
        function(event,editor) { // new line 
            // some code
        }
    );
    anoterFunction();
} 
```

Atom's behavior:

``` js
function outer(){

    fnWithCallback('someLongAttributeikeAnEventString', 
    function(event,editor) { // new line 
        // some code
    }
); // uncorrectly indented
anotherFunction();// uncorrectly indented too
}
```

Bracket's (not really better) behaviour:

``` js
function outer(){

    fnWithCallback('someLongAttributeikeAnEventString', 
                   function(event,editor) {
        // some code
    }
                  );
    anoterFunction();
}
```

Sublimes behaviour:

``` js
function outer(){

    fnWithCallback('someLongAttributeikeAnEventString', 
    function(event,editor) { // new line 
        // some code
    }
    );
    anoterFunction();
}
```
